    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Best GIC Rates 2026: 1-Year, 3-Year, and 5-Year Strategies",
    "description": "Compare the best GIC rates for 2026 across Canada. Understand the difference between cashable and non-redeemable GICs to lock in top yields.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Fire Maths"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between a cashable and non-redeemable GIC?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A cashable (or redeemable) GIC allows you to withdraw your money before the term ends without penalty, though it pays a lower interest rate. A non-redeemable GIC locks your money in for the full term but pays a significantly higher rate."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Are GICs a good investment for early retirement?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, GICs are an excellent tool for mitigating sequence of returns risk. By holding 1-3 years of living expenses in a GIC ladder, you ensure you have cash available during market downturns."
        }
